<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Executive Summary</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Sense International </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="_Ref375052554"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Sense International</span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sense International </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(SI) is an international development NGO that supports deafblind</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people and their families in countries where extreme poverty exists – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">India</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bangladesh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kenya</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Uganda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tanzania</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Peru</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Romania</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By working closely with families and professionals we supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ort deafblind people to develop vital communication and life skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SI works in active partnership with local organisations and governments to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> deliver appropriate educational, health and vocational services for deafblind people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> SI supports local disability and parent groups by offering them the training, backing and financial support needed to advocate for their needs and provide mutual support. Together we aim to spread the word about deafblindness and campaign for deafblind pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ople’s needs to be formally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and met.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a member of the Bond DDG, we are supporting the disability sector wide recommendations made in that submission and so have only included more specific recommendations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Executive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Governments need a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disability Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for the inclusion of people with disabilities, including a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">National Council of Disabled People</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Multi-disciplinary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  As part of this strategy there needs to be a single inter-departmental pathway whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ch deals with and coordinates the identification, assessment and treatment across all the governmental ministries. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Small scale Civil Society work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can provide innovative models for inclusive development.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People with complex needs such as deafblindness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are harder to reach than people with other disabilities and so are not benefitting from much of the work that DFID is doing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stigma </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and lack of understanding is standing in the way of deafblind people being identified which means that they are isolated and not benefitting from progress being made in development.  This needs to be addressed with national awareness programmes and trainin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g of teachers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health workers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and other professionals. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Teachers, health workers and others need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in order to understand how to include deafblind people in mainstream services.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">specialist knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of organisations like SI and its partners is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> needed to provide this training and to support deafblind people to develop the communication and mobility skills they need to be part of their families and communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Participation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of disabled people is a key element in the development of policy and pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actice around disability.  Deafblind people and their families are struggling to participate due to a lack of understanding of their needs, such as the provision of interpreters</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">How does</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline"> deafblindness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline"> affect people’s lives</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Deafblindness is a combination of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">hearing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> impairments. Some people are completely deaf and blind, but most have a little sight and/or hearing they can use. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a consequence they are unable to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> communicate with their parents and the o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">utside world</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> move around independently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">information and services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Deafblind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ness is a spectrum and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vary enormously in the levels of their disability. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> At one extreme of the spectrum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">individual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cognitive and physical disabilities in addition to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hearing and vision loss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and at the other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people have hearing and vision loss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whether deafblindness is congenital or acquired influences an individual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s communication methods and how they identify themselves. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e are talking about a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> highly diverse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in common the fact that they are a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> group </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">distinctive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">complex needs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From the social model there are specific barriers that prevent this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particularly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> marginalised group from accessing services.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-30.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We estimate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at least 2.85 million </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deafblind people amongst the 1 billion people with disabilities globally</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">eafblind individuals face multiple b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">arriers to Inclusion</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Society should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not just be based on what people can add economically, but instead reflect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> diversity of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a population </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> equal rights and opportunities.  There is a drive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to make this happen by mainstreaming disability but a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t present very few d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eafblind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people are being reached</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This is due to a number of different factors which we discuss below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stigma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People with complex needs and their families often face stigma within their communities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Equally, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hey are often ostracised by their families and have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">little or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">no relationship with society. This impedes identification by authorities and inclusion in society</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ultimately preventing access to the services, materials and r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ights individuals need to live.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is deafblind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, his</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mother said “Kevin was unable to walk, talk and see for a long time”. She continued, “We were isolated, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stigmatised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and hated by our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neighbours</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> just because of our son’s condition.  Some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neighbours</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> laughed at his strange disability, others stood in wonder at it.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“My husband fled when he realised that Jematia was deaf and blind, and claimed that I had brought curses to his family.  My mother-in-law was also threatening to kill me because of giving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> birth to such a child in their family.”  Eunice </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Identification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Identification of people with disabilities is hard enough but identification of people with complex disabilities is even harder. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The census is one way to identify the number of disabled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people in a country and the Washington Group on Disability Statistics</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been formulating questions over the last ten years or so that many countries include within their census’.  However, social stigma prevents many families bringing forward people wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h deafblindness for the census.  In addition to this, trainings for staff carrying out the census in complex disabilities are needed in order to facilitate their identification of this group.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This has much wider implications for inclusion and DFID’s work.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Issues of shame, embarrassment and fear prevent participation.  How people view deafblindness needs to change. If this doesn’t occur take up rates for any programme or project will never increase/reach target.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Communication</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Deafblind individuals have limited communication methods. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> They may use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> speech with the assistance of a hearing aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and lipreading</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or they may use sign language (possibly manually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> within a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">small visual frame</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or simplified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or they may use objects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to un</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">derstand what is happening</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  This means that i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is much harder for them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to communicate their needs, access their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rights or advocate for change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mobility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Deafblind people also face difficulties with mobility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  This can cause difficulties </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in familiar environments such as their own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">communities and moving to unfamiliar environments as may be necessary to go to school or work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Access to Information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Communication and mobility problems combine to make access to information difficult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for deafblind people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  This means that there may be government programmes and benefits that they would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be eligible for but which they know nothing about.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">What works</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The barriers discussed above need to be addressed for development to be inclusive of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people with d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eafblindness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  This section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some of the solutions that can be put in place.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Awareness campaigns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To develop an integrated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> bilateral approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, DFID can work with national governments on awareness programmes to create greater underst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">anding of these groups </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and combat discrimination and stigma.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or example in the late 1990’s the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> government ran a campaign about ‘See the person, not the disability’ featuring different disabled people and their lives.  The aim was to show that disabled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people are like anyone else, wanting friends, family, education, employment etc.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This campaign was obviously planned specifically for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> context but the concept could be adapted for different countries.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Lessons could also be learnt from the campaigns to address stigma and disc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rimination as a result of HIV/Aids</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Participation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Involvement of disabled people needs to be a key element of developing policy and practice for people with disabilities. It mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es governments and NGOs accountable to the people they serve, ensures transparency and ensures the sustainability of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policy and practices.  Deafblind people face more obstacles to participation than any other group of people, due to the profound communicat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion barriers they face.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">refore, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> input of deafblind people can ensure no-one is left </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">behind;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there are a number of different strands that need to be taken into account to achieve this. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Firstly, deafblind individuals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are able to contribute to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hese processes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should have the opportunity to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> included. SI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has supported the creation of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">National </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of Deafblind People </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in several of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where it works</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 126pt; text-indent:-45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SI India is working with an Adult Deafblind Forum. It aims </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to provide training and support deafblind adults to understand their rights and advocate for change.  The group is very reliant on interpreters and support workers to enable communication amongst the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but they are able to provide mutual support and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">advocate for change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Secondly, amongst deafblind people who can contribute to the development of policy and practice there is an urgent need for role models to inspire young people. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 126pt; text-indent:-45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith the support of SI Peru </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Minaya</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Magally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> took part in a lead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ership course in 2006 and started working for SI Peru in 2007. In 2012 Minaya was hired by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the National Council for the Integration of Persons with Disabilities,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> CONADIS as a "Deafblind Specialist". </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Her role</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is to develop trainings in the field of deafblin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dness, deafblind people rights and communication systems to public officials</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CONADIS has become the first public institution in the country to hire a person with deafblindness and Minaya acts a role model for deafblind young people in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Peru</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thirdly, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and provision </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of interpreters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Without interpreters with the appropriate skills to support them, many deafblind people are not able to take part in groups and forums.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 126pt; text-indent:-45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2010, as a result of campaigning by SI Peru a law was introduced, recog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing deafblindness as a unique disability.  The law gave deafblind people the right to guide interpreters to meet their communication and mobility needs.  In 2011 regulations were approved to set up an interpreter guide service and a register of these in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">terpreters.  These regulations are now starting to be implemented.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 126pt; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 126pt; text-indent:-45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">"Interpreters play a key role in helping deafblind people understand the world around them and participate fully in society. Without the support of a qualified interpreter many deafblind p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople would struggle to participate in a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conversation or group activities. Having this support allows a deafblind person to connect with others and feel part of a group." Kate Fitch, deputy head of public policy at deafblind charity Sense</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fourthly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it is important to involve parents or close family members as many children and adults with complex disabilities find it hard to be able to contribute to these processes themselves. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 126pt; text-indent:-45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3.4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I Kenya supported the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parents of Deafblind Persons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Kenya National Association of Parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in order to jointly lobby the government to increase provision for deafblind education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations met with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Ministry of Education </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the government committed to add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">itional teachers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> deafblind units and to recommending amendments to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ducation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ill of 2012 to include deafblindness. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Specialist knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Achieving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mainstreaming </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for children and adults with complex disabilities requires the input of specialist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">knowledge.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommunity workers who have this specialist knowledge are able to work with deafblind people, their families and communities to develop communication methods and independence skills. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In schools teaching assistants are needed to work with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deafblind children and make inclusion possible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his specialist knowledge include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an understanding of how to develop the communication and social skills; orientation and mobility skills; daily living skills; literacy, numeracy and vocational skills and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he perceptional awareness ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cessary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to achieve a level of independence.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Families and communities need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be included in this process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to enable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an understanding of how a person can contribute to family and community life.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Assistive Devices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To allow deafblind people a voice and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> them access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their rights they need assistance with communication</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and mobility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">involve t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he provision of assistive devices such as hearing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> aids, canes and wheelchairs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Training for mainstream staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Teachers, health workers and others need training in order to understand how to include deafblind people in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mainstream services.  The specialist knowledge of organisations like SI and its partners is needed to provide this training.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Small scale Civil So</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ciety work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can provide i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nnovative models for inclusive d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evelopment. Funding civil society programmes is only a small part of what DFID does but it is an important way of developing models that demonstrate to the community, the rest of civil society and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> government what is possible.  These model programmes act as evidence for effective ways to achieve inclusive development.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bangladesh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assistance,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> SI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme that is implemented by our partner CDD.  This programme has established </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> National Resource Centre on deafblindness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Dhaka,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the first of its kind in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bangladesh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. NRC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> partners with 16 development organizations from 16 districts and has reached about 800 deafblind people. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hub and spoke model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has emerged as an impo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rtant space offering information, training opportunities, referral services and counselling on deafblindness. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NRC has initiated a series of advocacy interventions aimed at the government and other parts of the development sector, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">media.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> These interventions have aimed to facilitate the recognition of deafblindness as a unique</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This was achieved in the inclusion of deafblindness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(with a definition) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as one of the eleven categories of disability in the Rights &amp; Protection of Pers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ons with Disabilities Act 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Single inter-departmental pathways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Individuals with complex needs require support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from multiple sectors of government (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">education, health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, labour). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here needs to be a single inter-departmental pathway which deals with and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> coordinates the identification, assessment and treatment across all the governmental ministries.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A multi disciplinary team, that includes parents, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will improve the quality of services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> enhance th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e sustainability of programmes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This pathway </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be specific to the issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Early Childhood Development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for children and a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Vocational Pathway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for adults which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would involve the Ministr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y of Education (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vocational training from 16-18</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the Ministry of Labour </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">help individuals with complex needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">find a niche in the market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This would help individuals migrate from school voca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tional work to the marketplace.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Policy Architecture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evidence from other sectors, such as HIV/Aids</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, suggests that the establishment of a National Council of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> affected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> combined with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">political leadership and resources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can result in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> transformational change for disabled people.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.9.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Once established, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">National Council of Disabled People</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the drawing up of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">multi-sectoral national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disability strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To be effective,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the council requires</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the political leadership, resources and accountability to people with disabilities to influence policy and practice across the government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 144pt; text-indent:-63pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.9.1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Evidence suggests that when located within the office </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prime Minister or President </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sential to ensure that the Council is effective.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 81pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.9.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national inclusive education programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> governments need to provide training to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">teachers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an appropriate curriculum; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appropriate assistive devices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> teaching assistants to support children in the classroom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to include families and communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and to ensure there is a focus on the individual needs of the child</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 144pt; text-indent:-63pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.9.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SI India </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is working with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ministry of Education as part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r flagship</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> educational programme- Sarva Shiksha Abhinya</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n (SSA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, to include deafblind children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">India</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is providing training to teachers in mainstream schools, on including children with deafblindness and multi-sensory</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> impairment, as part of the SSA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o far over 2,000 teachers across 16 states have been trained. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Example of how DFID could maximise the effectiveness of its intervention by equitably improving access to the Disability Rights Fund</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID contributes to the Disability Rights Fund and other organisations that support disabled peoples’ organisations (DPOs), as part of its commitment to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mainstreaming disability and enabling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the participation of disabled people themselves.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst we recog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nise the important work this enables, it is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an insufficient response to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reach highly excluded groups such as deafblind people.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Deafblind peoples’ associations or groups need interpreters to enable them to take part in meetings and other advocacy work.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e lack of available interpreters and the cost of funding those interpreters make it very difficult for deafblind people to either apply for funding for their own groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or take part in general DPOs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Governments need a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for the inclusion of people with disabilities, including a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">National Council of Disabled People</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  As part of its bilateral work, DFID is in a good position to work with national governments on this plan.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Multi-disciplinary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As part of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here needs to be a single inter-departmental pathway which deals with and coordinates the identification, assessment and treatment across all the governmental ministries. A multi disciplinary team, that includes parents, will improve the quali</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty of services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> enhance the sustainability of programmes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Small scale Civil Society work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can provide innovative models for inclusive development.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This fund</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing must continue to enable this work to happen.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Awareness campaigns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can addre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tigma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the need to identify people with complex needs such as deafblindness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As part of its bilateral work, DFID can work with national governments on awareness programmes to create greater understanding of these groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Teachers, health workers and others need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in order to understand how to include deafblind people in mainstream services.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specialist knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of organisations like SI and its partners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is needed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to provide this training and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to support deafblind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people to develop the communication and mobility skills they need to be part of their families and communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Participation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of disabled people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a key element in the development of policy and practice around disability.  Deafblind people and their fam</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ilies are struggling to participate due to a lack of understanding of their needs, such as the provision of interpreters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">The term deafblind is used throughout this paper to refer to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">people who are both deafblind and multi-sensory impaired.  Whilst we acknowledge the different medical categories for this group, they share very similar societal obstacles that inhibit or prevent access and inclusion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> WHO World Report on Disability 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/washington_group.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/washington_group.htm</span></a></p></body></html>